Q: I am a multi-node system, but I can't figure out how to get my BBS to pass
   the node number for the node switch. What do I do?


A:  Check your BBS package manual/documentation. Most multi-node systems have a
   symbol you enter in the batch file which tells the BBS to substitute the node
   number. Something like: C:\BBS\DOORS\LORD\START.BAT %N or *N or something!

Q: Man, I'm multi-node, and I'm using the DORINFO1.DEF dropfile. But, when
   someone on node two plays, Legend of the Red Dragon says it "CANNOT FIND
   DORINFO2.DEF" My BBS uses the DORINFO1.DEF for all nodes. What do I do now?

A: No problems. Use "(S)etup Nodes with BBS" option in LORDCFG, and change your
   dropfile type to a DORINFO1.DEF dropfile type. Right after you do this, it
   will give you an option of reading a DORINFO1.DEF for ALL nodes, or the other
   way.

Q: The door just locks up on the intro ANSI! How do I fix this?

A: Lock ups are NOT a part of Legend of the Red Dragon. Most likely you can fix
   the problem by changing your setup. Choose "(S)etup Nodes with BBS" option in
   LORDCFG and try a different setup. With 4.02 , it's now very easy to change
   settings, like locked baud rate.

   PERHAPS you are using a FOSSIL driver, but have Legend of the Red Dragon set
   to use Internal COM Routines? Change it to "Regular Fossil" and see what
   happens.

   If that don't do it, try this:

   Try using a fossil driver. Some high speed modems will not function correctly
   with Legend of the Red Dragon's internal COM routines, and using a FOSSIL
   driver is the only way to run the game. DON'T GET SCARED! This does not have
   to interfere with your BBS in any way. You can download a FOSSIL driver from
   most BBS's. A couple of suggested drivers are: X00.SYS by Raymond Gwinn or
   BNU by David Nugent. Consult the FOSSIL driver documentation for information
   on how to install it.

   If your BBS ALREADY runs with a FOSSIL, skip the fossil installation stuff!

Q: I am multi-node, and I am running Legend of the Red Dragon with no problems -
   But every time I  see a <MORE> prompt, it stops the game for a second or
   more! Why?

A: This is file access. This is how players in Legend of the Red Dragon can list
   other players, and see other players scores going up WHILE they play.

   The game communicates entirely by your hard drive. This way, as long as two
   games or more are running from the same DIRECTORY, it will work with the 
   multi-node functions (Online battles, sending mail and such).

   The fix: You could try a disk cache program. I personally use SMARTDRV that
   comes with MS-DOS. I run it like this from my AUTOEXEC.BAT:

   SMARTDRV 2000

