ÈÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍÍ¼
                          by Seth Able (Not an expert).

If a user with RIPterm 2.0 tries to play Legend of the Red Dragon, it will work,
but RIPterm will convert the icons incorrectly. (It uses the standard palette
only)

BUT.. We have a solution. Let interested users download LORDRIP2.ZIP, a file
that is NOT included in this archive, (only the 1.54 version is, because at this
time 2.0 is not very popular) but you can download it from my system, or check
major online services. 

LORDRIP2.ZIP contains BMP's of the original artwork correctly converted.  
Nothing is new, just compatible with 2.0.  (And of course, the BMP version is
not compatible with pre 2.0 Ripterm)

What is RIP? Well, it's a terminal emulation sort of like ANSI, except it uses a
VGA mode with 16 colors.  (A 256 color version of Legend of the Red Dragon could
be in your future, but only if RIP 256 is standardized.)

RIP stands for (R)emote (I)maging (P)rotocol.

To view ANSI, you need an ANSI capable terminal program, right?  Well, same 
with RIP - Legend of the Red Dragon v4.02  was tested with RIPterm V1.54.02.  

Telix For Windows was also tested successfully.

If your Terminal program supports RIP emulation and does not work with Legend of
the Red Dragon,  take it up with them. Legend of the Red Dragon's RIP uses no
"illegal" or nonstandard commands - Write them a letter with your complaints and
perhaps they will update their  program to FULLY support RIP.

Anyway, it allows users to use a mouse with the game, and view some nice
graphics in spots. The non-graphic menus are about the same length as the ANSI 
ones, so speed isn't a problem - EXCEPT for the larger ones that hold a lot of 
information - The graphics.  

Legend of the Red Dragon lets users DOWNLOAD a file, (LORDICON.ZIP) which
contains all the hand drawn icons. They then put it in their ICONS directory,
(If they are using RIP, they have one!) and RIP then recalls screens when Legend
of the Red Dragon asks it to.

So the large graphic screens don't slow the game down any - Even your 300 baud
users will see the INTRO.RIP file at full speed. 

When a user calls using RIPterm, the game will automatically notice that. It
will also check to see if the user has the correct files on his HD. If he
DOESN'T, it will let him download the LORDICON.ZIP file IN THE GAME, providing 
you have GSZ.EXE or DSZ.EXE, and told Legend of the Red Dragon where it was in
LORDCFG.EXE.

Playing the game without downloading the icons (LORDICON.ZIP) is NOT
RECOMMENDED!






Legend of the Red Dragon 4.02                                  Page 11
It doesn't matter if your BBS supports RIP or not, Legend of the Red Dragon
will. You will see strange symbols on your screen, instead of menus. These are
the RIP codes, do not re-boot your computer! This is normal, as of yet, there is
no RIP.SYS like ANSI.SYS that will automatically display the VGA RIP, but then
again, it would  surely slow down your system - and no one wants that.

Is RIP going to become a new standard? I don't know. I just implement what
people ask for most.

If a user complains it's not working, it's probably because they don't have the
latest version of RIPterm, (It will actually tell them that though when they 
play) or they have not UNZIPPED the LORDICON.ZIP file into the ICONS directory  
on their HD.

If the download LORDICON.ZIP option IN Legend of the Red Dragon does not work on
your system, you may have to put up LORDICON.ZIP in your file bases, so they can
download it from there.  

Well, if you didn't know anything about RIP before, hopefully you do now.

